<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Veratrum</i> <i>californicum</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous layer with <i>Achillea</i> <i>millefolium</i>, <i>Aconitum</i> <i>columbianum</i>, <i>Bistorta</i> <i>bistortoides</i>, <i>Carex</i> <i>microptera</i>, <i>Deschampsia</i> <i>cespitosa</i>, <i>Deschampsia</i> <i>elongata</i>, <i>Hordeum</i> <i>brachyantherum</i>, <i>Juncus</i> <i>nevadensis</i>, <i>Ligusticum</i> <i>californicum</i>, <i>Mertensia</i> <i>ciliata</i>, <i>Mimulus</i> <i>guttatus</i>, <i>Mimulus</i> <i>primuloides</i>, <i>Oreostemma</i> <i>alpigenum</i>, <i>Perideridia</i> <i>parishii</i>, <i>Phleum</i> <i>alpinum</i>, <i>Poa</i> <i>pratensis</i>, <i>Taraxacum</i> <i>officinale</i> and <i>Thalictrum</i> <i>fendleri</i>. Emergent trees and shrubs may be present at low cover. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 2 m; cover is intermittent to continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Veratrum californicum</i> > 50% relative cover in herbaceous layer (Potter 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Veratrum californicum</i> > 50% relative cover in the herbaceous layer; stands may have a significant cover of <i>Senecio triangularis</i> (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Raised portions of seasonally saturated meadows, stringer meadows adjacent to permanent streams, valley bottom meadows, wet meadows along slopes. Soils are usually sandy loams. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Veratrum californicum</i> as an OBL plant. </div>
</div>

        
