<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Veratrum californicum </i>is a tall, coarse perennial with large, elliptical leaves. It contains alkaloids that cause developmental malformations in sheep and cause dermatitis for some people. Often seen as a single stem or clumps in mountain meadows, this species can create extensive clones from underground rhizomes. Plants die back in the late summer as the soil dries. Plants in the state are var. <i>californicum. </i><br/>
<br/>
Stands tend to occupy edges or raised areas of wet montane meadows, often marking a transition between wet and dry ends of a soil moisture gradient in meadows. Many stands have forest edges and are adjacent to permanent streams as stringer meadows (Potter 2005). <i>V. californicum </i>is visually striking when present and appears to be an indicator of certain disturbance and moisture regimes. Cosgriff et al. (2004) considered that the presence of this native indicates a history of heavy livestock grazing, but Potter (2005) argued that this is not always the case. Stands vary in associated mesophytic herbs depending upon subtle moisture differences, grazing history, and other meadow impacts. Large stands indicate heavy grazing under some conditions (Manning and Padgett 1995, Potter 2005). The ecological similarity to other transitional meadow alliances characterized by <i>Carex nebrascensis, Deschampsia caespitosa, Poa pratensis, Senecio triangularis, </i>and <i>Trifolium longipes, </i>as well as woody riparian alliances characterized by <i>Populus tremuloides, Salix lemmonii, </i>and <i>S. orestera, </i>suggests a need to refine the role of moisture regimes and disturbance in describing the vegetation of these meadow/riparian systems. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
