    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Veratrum californicum</i> includes Northern California Coast (263A) and Southern California Mountains and Valleys (M262Bb, Be, Bm, Bo).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aa, Ac-l, An, Ap-r, At-u). Stands occur throughout montane portions of the section, especially in the Marble Mountains and Trinity Alps.</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gf). Stands exist in meadows at montane and elevations in the Warner Mountains (S. Smith 1998b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Da). Stands are found in the Carson River drainage.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba). Stands are common at meadow edges and on open slopes moistened by early summer snowmelt in the Yolla Bolly Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Keeler-Wolf 1974). The southernmost stand of<i> Populus tremuloides</i> in the North Coast Ranges is associated with a large stand of <i>V. californicum</i> on the south slopes of Black Rock Mountain.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-e, Eg-h, Ej-q, Et-u). This alliance is widespread in montane elevations. Stands occur in meadows in the Lake Tahoe region (Nachlinger 1985), at Harvey Monroe Hall Research Natural Area (Taylor 1984, see Cheng 2004), on the east side (Manning and Padgett 1995), and generally in the section where they are similar to stands of <i>Senecio triangularis</i> alliance (Potter 2005).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Df-g, Di-j, Dl-m). Stands occur throughout montane portions of the section, including from the Mount Shasta region to the Mount Lassen region.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Veratrum californicum </i>is resistant to grazing because of its toxicity to livestock. However, the herb-rich stands may be susceptible to livestock trampling, overuse through compaction, and loss of structure when sites are wet (Potter 2005). 

In evaluating ways to restore degraded herb-rich meadows, Cosgriff et al. (2004) concluded that mechanical removal of <i>V. californicum </i>was cumbersome and limited to gentle topography and sites lacking surface rocks. The application of herbicides (glyphosate) was more adaptable to all types of terrain. </div>
</div>

    

    

